Schedule SB, Part V — Summary of Plan Provisions
SUMMARY OF MAJOR PLAN PROVISIONS
Effective date and plan year Original plan: January 1, 1976
Restated plan: December 31, 2016
Plan year: January 1 through December 31, 2024
Most recent amendment Amendment Seventeen – October 27, 2023
Status of the plan As of December 31, 2016, the plan was closed to new entrants and all
benefit accruals were frozen.
Significant events that occurred In October 2023, Marsh McLennan amended the plan to provide a one-time
during the year lump-sum offering for certain participants with vested benefits who
terminated prior to April 1, 2023.
DEFINITIONS
(cid:127) Covered employees All salaried US employees of Marsh & McLennan Companies except for
employees of Mercer Benefits Administration, Marsh ClearSight, LLC, MMA,
Mercer Services, Mercer Systems Services LLC, Mercer WorkforcePro LLC,
and Dovetail Insurance Corporation. Also all temporary employees paid on
an hourly basis (with the same exceptions) who are credited with an hour of
service on or after January 1, 2010.
(cid:127) Participation Eligible employees who attained age 21 and 1 year of vesting service prior
to the plan freeze were eligible for plan entry.
(cid:127) Employee contributions None.
(cid:127) Vesting service All salaried service, and all service effective January 1, 2010, with Marsh &
McLennan Companies. Special rules apply for participants with a mix of
hourly and salaried service prior to 2010. Service with acquired companies
as specified in Appendix C of the plan document.
(cid:127) Credited service Salaried service, and all service effective January 1, 2010, with Marsh &
McLennan Companies, not including Mercer Services, Marsh ClearSight,
LLC, MMA, Mercer Systems Services LLC, Mercer Workforce Pro, LLC, or
Dovetail Insurance Corporation. Service with Sedgwick, Johnson and
Higgins and Organization Resources Counselors, Inc. (ORC) as specified in
their respective plan documents. As of December 31, 2016, all credited
service was frozen.
(cid:127) Pensionable earnings Base earnings, subject to the limit of IRC 401(a)(17). Excludes earnings
after December 31, 2016 plan freeze.
(cid:127) Final average earnings Average of annual base earnings for the consecutive five-year period of
service which produces the highest such average.
(cid:127) Primary Social Security Not applicable.
benefit
(cid:127) Covered Compensation Average of the Social Security taxable wage bases during the 35 years up
to and including the Social Security normal retirement age prior to
December 31, 2016 plan freeze.
(cid:127) Accrued benefit Normal retirement benefit (see below), based on accrued service and salary
earned prior to December 31, 2016 plan freeze.

2024 Form 5500 – Schedule SB Plan: MMC Retirement Plan
EIN/PN: 36-2668272/001
Schedule SB, Part V — Summary of Plan Provisions
NORMAL RETIREMENT
(cid:127) Eligibility Age 65
(cid:127) Benefit Part A: MMC Benefit – the sum of pieces (1) and (2) below:
(1) The final average pay accrued benefit as of December 31, 2005
calculated under the terms of the Plan in effect prior to January 1, 2006.
Participants who were actively employed on December 31, 2005 and whose
age and vesting service as of that date were at least 50 and 10,
respectively, have this piece of their benefit indexed. The indexing factor is
equal to their Average Annual Earnings at the earlier of termination and
December 31, 2016 divided by their Average Annual Earnings as of
December 31, 2005.
(2) The excess of (i) over (ii), for each year after 2005, frozen effective
December 31, 2016
(i) For each of the first 30 years of benefit service, 1.6% of a participant’s
annual earnings, and 1% of such earnings for each year of benefit service in
excess of 30 years
(ii) For each of the first 35 years of benefit service only, 0.4% of the
smaller of (a) and (b):
(a) a participant’s covered compensation as defined above
(b) a participant’s annual earnings
Part B: Johnson & Higgins Benefit – Applies only to participants who were
actively employed by Johnson & Higgins on March 27, 1997 and remained
continuously employed by MMC through December 31, 1997. The sum of
pieces (1) and (2) below:
(1) The MMC Benefit (Part A) as described above with service credited from
January 1, 1998. The accrual rate is determined using length of benefit
service from both J&H and MMC.
(2) The Frozen Accrued Benefit as of December 31, 1997 under the
Johnson & Higgins Retirement Income Plan as indexed with base salary
growth through date of termination. The indexing factor is equal to the
participant’s Average Annual Earnings at termination (frozen December 31,
2016) divided by the participant’s Average Annual Earnings at December
31, 1997. This indexing factor was unaffected by changes to the provisions
of the Plan effective January 1, 2006 and continued to be applied in the
same manner until frozen on December 31, 2016.
Part C: Sedgwick Benefit – Applies only to participants who were employed
by Sedgwick on November 3, 1998 and remained continuously employed by
MMC through December 31, 1999. The sum of pieces (1) and (2) below:
(1) The MMC Benefit (Part A) as described above with service credited from
January 1, 2000. The accrual rate is determined using length of benefit
service from both Sedgwick and MMC.
(2) The Frozen Accrued Benefit as of December 31, 1999 under the
Sedgwick Retirement Plan as indexed with base salary growth through date
of termination. The indexing factor is equal to the participant’s Average
Annual Earnings at termination (frozen December 31, 2016) divided by the
participant’s Average Annual Earnings at December 31, 1999. This indexing
factor was unaffected by changes to the provisions of the Plan effective
January 1, 2006 and continued to be applied in the same manner until
frozen on December 31, 2016

Schedule SB, Part V — Summary of Plan Provisions
(cid:127) Benefit (continued) Part D: Organization Research Counselors Benefit – Applies only to
participants previously employed by ORC. The sum of pieces (1) and (2)
below:
(1) The MMC Benefit (Part A) as described above with service credited from
August 1, 2010.
(2) The Frozen Accrued Benefit as of July 31, 2009 under the ORC Plan.
Former DBAS employees who became employees of Mercer Benefits
Administration effective January 1, 2005 (other than those at least age 45
with at least 5 years of service as of December 31, 2004 who elected
otherwise) had their accruals under the plan frozen as of December 31,
2004. Such Mercer Benefits Administration employees who have either 1)
reached age 40 and completed five years of service as of December 31,
2004; or 2) completed 10 years of service as of December 31, 2004 (the
“Mercer Benefits Administration indexed group”) will have their MMC
Retirement benefit (Part A) determined based on their service as of
December 31, 2004 and on their salary as of the earlier of the date they
leave Mercer Benefits Administration and December 31, 2005.
In the case of certain other acquired companies, the foregoing provisions
generally apply only in respect of service on or after the date of acquisition,
with service before that date being recognized in benefits accrued under
each such acquired company's former plan, if any.
For participants with earnings in excess of the 401(a)(17) compensation
limit, special transition rules may apply to the calculation of the benefit.
EARLY RETIREMENT
(cid:127) Eligibility Termination on or after attainment of age 55 and completion of 5 years of
service.
(cid:127) Benefit Calculated using benefit service, earnings and covered compensation at the
earlier of early retirement date and December 31, 2016 assuming constant
Social Security wage bases after that date.
For accrued benefits earned through December 31, 2005, the accrued
benefit is reduced by 4% for each year that the early retirement date
precedes age 62. For accrued benefits earned after December 31, 2005, the
accrued benefit is reduced by 5% for each year that the early retirement
date precedes age 65.
The December 31, 1997 Frozen Accrued Benefit under the Johnson &
Higgins Retirement Income Plan (indexed with base salary growth) is
reduced by 6% for each year that the early retirement date precedes age
62.
The December 31, 1999 Frozen Accrued Benefit under the Sedgwick
Retirement Plan (indexed with base salary growth) is reduced by 4% for
each year that the early retirement date precedes age 65. However, for
participants born after 1954, the reduction is 6% per year between ages 55
and 57.
The July 31, 2009 Frozen Accrued Benefit under the ORC Plan is reduced
by 3% for each year that the early retirement date precedes age 65.

for each year that the early retirement date precedes age 65.

Higgins Retirement Income Plan (indexed with base salary growth) is
reduced by 6% for each year that the early retirement date precedes
age 65.
- The December 31, 1999 Frozen Accrued Benefit under the Sedgwick
Retirement Plan (indexed with base salary growth) is reduced by 4% for
each year that the early retirement date precedes age 65. However, for
participants born after 1954, the reduction is 6% per year between ages
55 and 57.
- The July 31, 2009 Frozen Accrued Benefit under the ORC Plan is
reduced by 3% for each year that the early retirement date precedes
age 65.

were actively employed at the rate of pay in effect at date of disability.

2024 Form 5500 – Schedule SB Plan: MMC Retirement Plan
EIN/PN: 36-2668272/001
Schedule SB, Part V — Summary of Plan Provisions
(cid:127) Optional forms (i) Single life annuity (married participant)
(ii) A contingent annuity option of 50%, 66 2/3%, 75% or 100%, in favor of
any designated beneficiary;
(iii) A period-certain option, limited to 5, 10, 15 or 20 years, so long as the
period-certain does not extend beyond the participant's life expectancy; or
(iv) Social Security level income option, under which increased payments
are made until commencement of Social Security benefits at age 62, at
which time the payments are reduced by the expected amount of such
Social Security benefits.
(v) In the case of a former Sedgwick employee, the combined qualified plan
benefits may be paid in a lump sum actuarial equivalent form if such
actuarial equivalent is less than $20,000 (subject to consent of participant
and spouse). Furthermore, former employees of VOSCO are entitled to the
actuarial equivalent of their accrued benefit under that prior plan to be paid
as a lump sum. The lump sum is payable once the participant becomes
retirement eligible. Former Noble Lowndes employees are entitled to the
actuarial equivalent of their accrued benefit under that prior plan to be paid
as a lump sum, as long as they terminate after becoming eligible to retire.
Notwithstanding the above, a lump sum will be paid if the present value of
benefits does not exceed $1,000 ($3,500 prior to March 28, 2005) at the
time of termination. Effective January 1, 2008, the interest rates and
mortality table used are those mandated by the Pension Protection Act of
2006.
MISCELLANEOUS
(cid:127) Maximum compensation Compensation for any 12-month period used to determine accrued benefits
may not exceed the limits in IRC Section 401(a)(17) for the calendar year in
which the 12-month period begins. This limit is indexed annually. For2016
(the last year in which the Plan provided benefit accruals), the limit was
$265,000.
(cid:127) Maximum benefits Annual benefits may not exceed the limits in IRC Section 415. This limit is
indexed annually. For 2024, the limit is $275,000.

─ Plan amendments: See above.

dates before the valuation date but are ignored for annuity starting dates on or after the
valuation date.

accruals.

INDEPENDENT AUDITOR’S REPORT
To the Marsh & McLennan Benefits Administration Committee and Plan Administrator of the Marsh &
McLennan Companies Retirement Plan
Scope and Nature of the ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) Audit
We have performed audits of the financial statements of Marsh & McLennan Companies Retirement
Plan (the “Plan”), an employee benefit plan subject to the Employee Retirement Income Security Act
of 1974 (ERISA), as permitted by ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) (ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) audit).
The financial statements comprise the statements of net assets available for benefits as of December
31, 2024 and 2023, and the related statement of changes in net assets available for benefits for the
year ended December 31, 2024, and the related notes to the financial statements.
Management, having determined it is permissible in the circumstances, has elected to have the audits
of the Plan’s financial statements performed in accordance with ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) pursuant
to 29 CFR 2520.103-8 of the Department of Labor’s Rules and Regulations for Reporting and
Disclosure under ERISA. As permitted by ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C), our audits need not extend to
any statements or information related to assets held for investment of the Plan (investment
information) by a bank or similar institution or insurance carrier that is regulated, supervised, and
subject to periodic examination by a state or federal agency, provided that the statements or
information regarding assets so held are prepared and certified to by the bank or similar institution or
insurance carrier in accordance with 29 CFR 2520.103-5 of the Department of Labor’s Rules and
Regulations for Reporting and Disclosure under ERISA (qualified institution).
Management has obtained certifications from a qualified institution as of December 31, 2024 and
2023, and for the year ended December 31, 2024, stating that the certified investment information, as
described in Note 8 to the financial statements, is complete and accurate.
Opinion
In our opinion, based on our audits and on the procedures performed as described in the Auditor’s
Responsibilities for the Audit of the Financial Statements section
• The amounts and disclosures in the accompanying financial statements, other than those agreed
to or derived from the certified investment information, are presented fairly, in all material
respects, in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of
America.
• The information in the accompanying financial statements related to assets held by and certified to
by a qualified institution agrees to, or is derived from, in all material respects, the information
prepared and certified by an institution that management determined meets the requirements of
ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C).

Basis for Opinion
We conducted our audits in accordance with auditing standards generally accepted in the United
States of America (GAAS). Our responsibilities under those standards are further described in the
Auditor’s Responsibilities for the Audit of the Financial Statements section of our report. We are
required to be independent of the Plan and to meet our other ethical responsibilities, in accordance
with the relevant ethical requirements relating to our audits. We believe that the audit evidence we
have obtained is sufficient and appropriate to provide a basis for our ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) audit
opinion.
Responsibilities of Management for the Financial Statements
Management is responsible for the preparation and fair presentation of the financial statements in
accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America, and for the
design, implementation, and maintenance of internal control relevant to the preparation and fair
presentation of financial statements that are free from material misstatement, whether due to fraud or
error. Management’s election of the ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) audit does not affect management’s
responsibility for the financial statements.
In preparing the financial statements, management is required to evaluate whether there are
conditions or events, considered in the aggregate, that raise substantial doubt about the Plan’s ability
to continue as a going concern for one year after the date that the financial statements are available
to be issued.
Management is also responsible for maintaining a current plan instrument, including all plan
amendments, administering the Plan, and determining that the Plan’s transactions that are presented
and disclosed in the financial statements are in conformity with the Plan’s provisions, including
maintaining sufficient records with respect to each of the participants, to determine the benefits due
or which may become due to such participants.
Auditor’s Responsibilities for the Audit of the Financial Statements
Except as described in the Scope and Nature of the ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) Audit section of our
report, our objectives are to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements as a
whole are free from material misstatement, whether due to fraud or error, and to issue an auditor’s
report that includes our opinion. Reasonable assurance is a high level of assurance but is not absolute
assurance and therefore is not a guarantee that an audit conducted in accordance with GAAS will
always detect a material misstatement when it exists. The risk of not detecting a material
misstatement resulting from fraud is higher than for one resulting from error, as fraud may involve
collusion, forgery, intentional omissions, misrepresentations, or the override of internal control.
Misstatements are considered material if there is a substantial likelihood that, individually or in the
aggregate, they would influence the judgment made by a reasonable user based on the financial
statements.
In performing an audit in accordance with GAAS, we:
• Exercise professional judgment and maintain professional skepticism throughout the audit.
• Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement of the financial statements, whether due to
fraud or error, and design and perform audit procedures responsive to those risks. Such
procedures include examining, on a test basis, evidence regarding the amounts and disclosures in
the financial statements.
• Obtain an understanding of internal control relevant to the audit in order to design audit
procedures that are appropriate in the circumstances, but not for the purpose of expressing an
opinion on the effectiveness of the Plan’s internal control. Accordingly, no such opinion is
expressed.
• Evaluate the appropriateness of accounting policies used and the reasonableness of significant
accounting estimates made by management, as well as evaluate the overall presentation of the
financial statements.
2

• Conclude whether, in our judgment, there are conditions or events, considered in the aggregate,
that raise substantial doubt about the Plan’s ability to continue as a going concern for a
reasonable period of time.
Our audits did not extend to the certified investment information, except for obtaining and reading the
certification, comparing the certified investment information with the related information presented
and disclosed in the financial statements, and reading the disclosures relating to the certified
investment information to assess whether they are in accordance with the presentation and disclosure
requirements of accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America.
Accordingly, the objective of an ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) audit is not to express an opinion about
whether the financial statements as a whole are presented fairly, in all material respects, in
accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America.
We are required to communicate with those charged with governance regarding, among other
matters, the planned scope and timing of the audit, significant audit findings, and certain internal
control-related matters that we identified during the audit.
Other Matter — Supplemental Schedules Required by ERISA
The supplemental schedule of assets (held at end of year) as of December 31, 2024 and the
supplemental schedule of reportable transactions for the year ended December 31, 2024 are
presented for purposes of additional analysis and are not a required part of the financial statements
but are supplementary information required by the Department of Labor’s Rules and Regulations for
Reporting and Disclosure under ERISA. Such information is the responsibility of management and was
derived from and relates directly to the underlying accounting and other records used to prepare the
financial statements. The information included in the supplemental schedules, other than that agreed
to or derived from the certified investment information, has been subjected to auditing procedures
applied in the audit of the financial statements and certain additional procedures, including comparing
and reconciling such information directly to the underlying accounting and other records used to
prepare the financial statements or to the financial statements themselves, and other additional
procedures in accordance with GAAS. For information included in the supplemental schedules that
agreed to or is derived from the certified investment information, we compared such information to
the related certified investment information.
In forming our opinion on the supplemental schedules, we evaluated whether the supplemental
schedules, other than the information agreed to or derived from the certified investment information,
including their form and content, are presented in conformity with the Department of Labor’s Rules
and Regulations for Reporting and Disclosure under ERISA.
In our opinion:
• The form and content of the supplemental schedules, other than the information in the
supplemental schedules that agreed to or is derived from the certified investment information, are
presented, in all material respects, in conformity with the Department of Labor's Rules and
Regulations for Reporting and Disclosure under ERISA.
• The information in the supplemental schedules related to assets held by and certified to by a
qualified institution agrees to, or is derived from, in all material respects, the information prepared
and certified by an institution that management determined meets the requirements of ERISA
Section 103(a)(3)(C).

1. Description of the Plan
General
Marsh & McLennan Companies, Inc. (the "Company", "Employer", or "Plan Sponsor") established the Marsh &
McLennan Companies Retirement Plan (the "Plan") to provide retirement benefits for its eligible employees.
Under the Plan, eligible employees in the United States ("U.S."), as well as certain U.S. expatriates working
abroad, became eligible participants in the Plan after the completion of one year of service and the attainment of
age 21 and were classified as a U.S. regular or temporary employee. On December 31, 2016, the Plan was
frozen and participants ceased to accrue any benefits under the Plan after that date. The Plan is closed to new
entrants and any employee who was not a participant in the Plan on December 31, 2016, is not eligible to
participate in the Plan.
Generally, a participant became fully vested in the Plan after the earlier of five years of vesting service or age 65.
Certain U.S. subsidiaries are not included in the Plan. The Plan is subject to the provisions of the Employee
Retirement Income Security Act of 1974 ("ERISA"), as amended. Participants should refer to the summary plan
description located in the Marsh & McLennan Companies Benefits Handbook accessible via https://
careers.marshmclennan.com/global/en/us-benefits and the Plan document for more complete information.
The Plan’s investments are in the Marsh & McLennan Master Retirement Trust (the "Master Trust"). The assets of
the Master Trust at December 31, 2024 and 2023 were held by The Northern Trust Company (the “Trustee”). All
expenses of administering the Plan, to the extent not paid for by the Company, are paid from the Plan's assets as
provided in the Plan document. Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation ("PBGC") premiums are included in
administrative expenses in the accompanying statement of changes in net assets available for benefits and are
shown as other expenses in the Form 5500.
The Marsh & McLennan Companies Benefit Administration Committee ("BAC") is the Plan administrator
responsible for the overall administration and operation of the Plan. Certain administrative functions are
performed by employees of the Company or its subsidiaries. The Marsh & McLennan Companies Benefit
Investment Committee is the investment fiduciary responsible for the investment and monitoring of Plan assets.
Merger of the JLT (USA) Employees’ Retirement Plan
The JLT (USA) Employees’ Retirement Plan (the "JLT Plan") was merged into the Plan, effective December 31,
2024. The benefits accrued by a JLT Plan participant under the JLT Plan (frozen as of July 31, 2005) at December
31, 2024 are determined under the terms of the JLT Plan, which are incorporated into the Plan. The JLT Plan trust
fund was also merged into the Master Trust effective December 31, 2024. The JLT Plan participants do not earn
any new accruals with respect to their JLT Plan benefits, nor earn any new accruals under the Plan. The merger
did not affect the participants' pension benefits because the benefits provisions of the merged JLT Plan were
incorporated into the Plan.
As a result of this merger, assets in the amount of $37,787,709 and accumulated plan benefit liabilities in the
amount of $40,899,555 were transferred to the Plan.
Pension Benefits
Under the Plan there may be various calculations to determine the amount of a participant’s benefit: a calculation
for pre-2006 benefits and a calculation for post-2005 benefits (reflecting a Plan amendment effective on January
1, 2006). A participant’s benefit calculation depends upon their dates of service. A participant that has service
dates before and after January 1, 2006, will have their service bifurcated and calculated as separate sums to be
added together for a total benefit amount.
Pre-January 1, 2006 Service
The factors in the pre-January 1, 2006 service formula that are used to calculate the participant’s annual benefit
earned at December 31, 2005 are the participant’s final average salary, subject to the Internal Revenue Code
("IRC") limits for qualified plans, length of benefit service and the Plan's benefit percentage.
6

The formula for the Plan to determine the participant’s annual benefit (payable as a single life annuity on or after
age 65) is as follows:
For the first 30 years (360 months) of benefit service: 1.6% of the participant’s final average salary at December
31, 2005 multiplied by the participant’s years and months of benefit service before 2006 up to a maximum of 30
years; plus (if applicable), for benefit service beyond 30 years (360 months): 1.0% of the participant’s final
average salary at December 31, 2005, multiplied by the participant’s years and months of benefit service before
2006 in excess of 30 years; minus, for the first 35 years (420 months) of benefits service, an amount representing
the participant’s Social Security retirement benefits, which is equal to 0.4% multiplied by the participant’s covered
compensation (or final average salary, if less) at December 31, 2005, multiplied by the participant’s years and
months of benefit service before 2006 up to 35 years.
The benefit earned for service before January 1, 2006, payable as a single life annuity on or after age 65 will not
change in the future, unless the participant is eligible for a transition benefit. The benefit payable by the Plan does
not include any benefit the participant may be eligible for under Social Security. The eligible base salary used in
determining the participant’s final average salary is subject to the IRC limits for a qualified plan.
Post-December 31, 2005 Service
A Plan benefit for service on and after January 1, 2006 will be determined for each month of eligible service using
a formula based on the participant’s eligible monthly base salary, subject to Federal limits for qualified plans, and
the Plan's benefit percentage.
The post-December 31, 2005 service formula for the Plan to determine the participant’s annual benefit accrued for
each month of service (payable as a single life annuity on or after age 65) is as follows:
For the first 30 years (360 months) of benefit service including months of benefit service taken into account to
calculate any pre-2006 benefit: 1.6% multiplied by the participant’s eligible monthly base salary; plus (if
applicable), for benefit service beyond 30 years (360 months) including months of benefit service taken into
account to calculate any pre-2006 benefit: 1.0% multiplied by the participant’s eligible monthly base salary subject
to IRC limits for qualified plans; minus, for the first 35 years (420 months) of benefit service: an amount
representing the participant’s Social Security retirement benefit, which is equal to 0.4% multiplied by the
participant’s monthly covered compensation (or the participant’s eligible monthly base salary, if less).
The monthly benefit payable in the form of an annuity for the participant’s lifetime will be one-twelfth (1/12) of the
annual amount determined by aggregating the accruals determined under the above formula for all of the
participant’s months of benefit service on or after December 31, 2005.
Payment of Plan Benefits
If the participant has eligible service before and after January 1, 2006, the participant’s December 31, 2005
accrued benefit will be based solely on the participant’s eligible benefit service and the participant’s final average
base salary as of that date, unless the participant is eligible for a transition benefit. A transition benefit is provided
for participants who were actively employed on December 31, 2005 and whose age and vesting service as of that
date were at least 50 and 10, respectively. These participants will have the accrued benefit increased in
proportion to the increase in their average annual earnings between December 31, 2005 and the earlier of their
date of termination of their employment or December 31, 2016. The participant’s accrued benefit on or after
January 1, 2006 will be calculated under the current formula and will be based on the participant’s eligible monthly
base salary, length of benefit service and the Plan's benefit percentage.
Benefits are normally payable at age 65; however, payments may begin at any time at or after age 55 and the
completion of five years of service, at the election of the participant, subject to a reduction in pre-2006 benefits
generally equal to 4% for each year the early retirement date precedes age 62 and subject to a reduction in
post-2005 benefits generally equal to 5% for each year the early retirement date precedes age 65.
If a vested employee dies while actively employed or terminates and dies before their Plan benefit begins, a death
benefit is paid to the surviving spouse or the surviving domestic partner. A surviving spouse is the legal spouse of
the employee who has been married to such employee for at least one year at the time of the employee’s death. A
surviving domestic partner is the legal domestic partner of the employee as defined by the Plan who has been the
domestic partner of the employee for at least one year at the time of the employee’s death. If an employee dies
after the benefits commence, the payments will be received by the beneficiary pursuant to the Plan document.

2. Summary of Accounting Policies
Basis of Accounting
The accompanying financial statements have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally
accepted in the United States of America (“GAAP”).
Use of Estimates
The preparation of financial statements in accordance with U.S. GAAP requires management to make estimates
and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets, liabilities and changes therein, disclosure of
contingent assets and liabilities, and the actuarial present value of accumulated plan benefits and changes therein
at the date of the financial statements. Actual results could differ from those estimates.
Risk and Uncertainties
The Master Trust holds various investment instruments including short-term investment funds, employer stock and
corporate stocks, U.S. Government securities, corporate debt instruments, partnership interests, swaps, interests
in common/collective trusts, interests in pooled separate accounts, interests in registered investment companies,
and real estate investment trusts.
Investment securities, in general, are exposed to various risks such as geopolitical or macroeconomic conditions
including from multiple major wars and global conflicts, tariffs or changes in trade policies, slower GDP growth or
recession, lower interest rates, capital markets volatility, and inflation. Concentrations of these risks are generally
limited due to diversification by investment style within each asset class, diversification by investment manager,
diversification by industry sectors and issuers, and the dispersion of investments across many geographic areas.
Due to the level of risk associated with certain investment instruments, it is reasonably possible that changes in
the values of investment instruments will occur in the near term and that such changes could materially affect the
amounts reported in the financial statements.
Plan contributions are made and the actuarial present value of accumulated plan benefits are reported based on
certain assumptions pertaining to interest rates, inflation rates, and employee demographics, all of which are
subject to change. Due to uncertainties inherent in estimations and assumptions, it is at least reasonably possible
that changes in these estimates and assumptions in the near term would be material to the financial statements.
Investment Valuation and Income Recognition
The Master Trust’s investments are stated at their fair value or estimated fair value. If available, quoted market
prices are used to value investments. Certain securities are traded in foreign markets in local currencies. The cost
and market value of these securities are reported in U.S. dollars, translated at the foreign exchange rate in effect
at the end of each year. Refer to Note 4, Fair Value Measurements, for the discussion on fair value
measurements.
Purchases and sales of securities are recorded on a trade-date basis. Interest income is recorded on the accrual
basis. Dividends are recorded on the ex-dividend date. Net appreciation (depreciation) in fair value of investments
includes the Master Trust’s gains and losses on investments bought and sold as well as held during the year.
Payment of Benefits
Benefit payments to participants are recorded upon distribution.
Administrative Expenses
Administrative expenses incurred by the Plan in 2024 totaled $20,233,670 and were primarily for PBGC fees,
investment management fees, third-party administrator, auditor and trustee fees. The Plan Sponsor paid for
actuarial services provided by Mercer (a wholly-owned subsidiary of the Company). The Plan Sponsor also
provides accounting and other administrative services to the Plan.

4. Fair Value Measurements
U.S. GAAP provides a framework for measuring fair value. This framework provides a fair value hierarchy that
prioritizes the inputs to valuation techniques used to measure fair value as follows: Level 1, which refers to
securities valued using unadjusted quoted prices from active markets for identical assets; Level 2, which refers to
securities not traded on an active market but for which observable market inputs are readily available; Level 3,
which refers to securities valued based on significant unobservable inputs; and Net Asset Value ("NAV"), which
refers to investments valued using net asset value as a practical expedient. Assets and liabilities are classified in
their entirety based on the lowest level of input that is significant to the fair value measurement.

Transfers between levels — The availability of observable market data is monitored to assess the appropriate
classification of financial instruments within the fair value hierarchy. Changes in economic conditions or model-
based valuation techniques may require the transfer of financial instruments from one fair value level to another.
The significance of transfers between levels is evaluated based upon the nature of the financial instrument and
size of the transfer relative to total net assets available for benefits. Valuation techniques maximize the use of
relevant observable inputs and minimize the use of unobservable inputs. There were no transfers between levels
in 2024 or 2023.
Asset Valuation Techniques — Valuation techniques maximize the use of relevant observable inputs and
minimize the use of unobservable inputs. The following is a description of the valuation methodologies used for
assets measured at fair value. There have been no changes in the methodologies used at December 31, 2024
and 2023.
Short-term investment funds: High-grade money market instruments valued using a valuation technique that
results in price per share of $1.00.
The Company’s common stock: Valued at the closing price reported on the New York Stock Exchange.
Common stocks, preferred stocks, convertible equity securities and rights/warrants (included in Corporate stocks):
Valued at the closing price reported on the primary exchange.
U.S. Government bonds (included in U.S. Government securities): The fair value of U.S. government bonds is
estimated by pricing models that utilize observable market data including quotes, spreads and data points for yield
curves.
U.S. agency securities (included in U.S. Government securities): U.S. agency securities are comprised of two
main categories consisting of agency issued debt and mortgage pass-throughs. Agency issued debt securities are
valued by benchmarking market-derived prices to quoted market prices and trade data for identical or comparable
securities. Mortgage pass-throughs include certain "To-be-announced" (TBA) securities and mortgage pass-
through pools. TBA securities are generally valued using quoted market prices or are benchmarked thereto. Fair
value of mortgage pass-through pools are model driven with respect to spreads of the comparable TBA security.
Corporate bonds (included in corporate obligations): The fair value of corporate bonds is estimated using recently
executed transactions, market price quotations (where observable) and bond spreads. The spread data used are
for the same maturity as the bond. If the spread data does not reference the issuer, then data that reference a
comparable issuer are used. When observable price quotations are not available, fair value is determined based
on cash flow models.
Commercial mortgage-backed and asset-backed securities (included in corporate obligations): Fair value is
determined using discounted cash flow models. Observable inputs are based on trade and quote activity of bonds
with similar features including issuer vintage, purpose of underlying loan (first or second lien), prepayment speeds
and credit ratings. The discount rate is the combination of the appropriate rate from the benchmark yield curve
and the discount margin based on quoted prices.
11

Private equity and real estate partnerships: Investments in private equity and real estate partnerships are valued
based on the NAV reported by the manager of the corresponding partnership, which is used as a practical
expedient to estimate fair value. The NAV is based on various analyses on the underlying holdings in each
partnership, including financial valuation models and projections, comparable valuations from the public markets,
and precedent private market transactions.
Common/collective trusts: Valued at the NAV of units of a bank collective trust. The NAV, as provided by the
trustee, is used as a practical expedient to estimate fair value. The NAV is based on the fair value of the
underlying investments held by the fund less its liabilities. This practical expedient is not used when it is
determined to be probable that the fund will sell the investment for an amount different than the reported net asset
value. Were the Master Trust to initiate a full redemption of the collective trust, the investment advisor reserves
the right to temporarily delay withdrawal from the trust in order to ensure that securities liquidations will be carried
out in an orderly business manner.
Real estate investments trusts (included in Other investments): Valued at the closing price reported on an
exchange.
State, municipal and foreign bonds (included in Other investments): Valued using an average of institutional bid
and ask evaluation prices when both are present. When these are not available, proprietary pricing models are
used to estimate the price a dealer would pay for a security or accept to sell a security.
Swap assets and liabilities: Fair values for interest rate swaps, equity index swaps and inflation swaps are
estimated using a discounted cash flow pricing model. These models use observable market data such as
contractual fixed rate, broker quotes, spot equity price or index value and dividend data. The fair values of credit
default swaps are estimated using an income approach model which determines expected cash flows based on
default probabilities from the issuer specific credit spread curve and credit loss recovery rates, both of which are
dependent on market quotes.

5. Accumulated Plan Benefits
Accumulated plan benefits are those future periodic payments, including lump-sum distributions, that are
attributable under the Plan’s provisions for services rendered by employees as of the valuation date.
Accumulated plan benefits include benefits expected to be paid to (1) retired or terminated employees or their
beneficiaries and (2) present employees or their beneficiaries. Benefits payable as a result of retirement, death,
disability or termination of employment are included to the extent they are deemed attributable to employee
service rendered to the valuation date. The actuarial present value of accumulated plan benefits of the Plan was
determined by Mercer, a wholly-owned subsidiary of the Company and a party-in-interest of the Plan. The
amount results from applying actuarial assumptions to adjust the accumulated plan benefits to reflect the time
value of money (through discounts for interest) and the probability of payment (by means of decrements such
as for death, disability, withdrawal, or retirement) between the valuation date and the expected date of payment.
The effect of plan amendments on accumulated plan benefits are recognized during the year in which such
amendments are adopted. There were no amendments effective January 1, 2025 recognized in the actuarial
present value of accumulated plan benefits.
The following summarizes the more significant assumptions used to determine the actuarial present value of
accumulated plan benefits in the actuary's report.
Mortality For December 31, 2024 and December 31, 2023, pre-commencement mortality was
based on the Pri-2012 white collar mortality tables for males and females, and the
post-commencement mortality was based on the Mercer Industry Longevity
Experience Study (MILES) Banks, Financial Services and Insurance Industry Tables.
For both 2024 and 2023, the improvement scale was MMP-2021 applied
generationally.
Discount Rate 5.76% at December 31, 2024 and 5.52% at December 31, 2023.
Retirement Age For active participants, the retirement age is in accordance with a scale developed on
the basis of actual experience. For both December 31, 2024, and December 31,
2023, the average expected retirement age is 62. For terminated vested participants,
the expected retirement age was 62 if under 62 or 65 if over 62 (current age if greater
than 65).
The foregoing actuarial assumptions are based on the presumption that the Plan will continue indefinitely. If the
Plan were to terminate, different actuarial assumptions and other factors would be applicable in determining the
actuarial present value of accumulated plan benefits. Due to uncertainties inherent in the estimations and
assumptions process, it is at least reasonably possible that certain changes in these estimates and assumptions
could be material to the financial statements.

6. Funding Policy
The Plan is a defined benefit plan for which all contributions are made by the Company. The Company contributes
annually a minimum of such amounts as are necessary to provide the Plan with assets sufficient to meet the
actuarially computed benefits to be paid to Plan participants as determined under ERISA. For the Plan years
ended December 31, 2024 and 2023, the Plan met minimum funding requirements as set forth by ERISA;
therefore no contributions were required to be made to the Plan.
The yield (interest, dividends and net realized and unrealized appreciation (depreciation)) on investments of the
Plan serves to reduce or increase future contributions that would otherwise be required to provide for the defined
level of benefits under the Plan document.
Although it has not expressed an intention to do so, the Company has the right to discontinue its contributions at
any time and to terminate the Plan subject to the provisions set forth in ERISA.
7. Plan Termination
If the Plan is terminated and contributions are completely discontinued, participants employed on the date of
termination shall vest in their accrued benefit and any funds held in trust or under insurance contracts will be
allocated and distributed in the manner set forth in Section 4044 of ERISA to persons entitled to benefits upon
termination of the Plan. Any funds or property remaining in the Master Trust after satisfaction of liabilities to
participants, payment of expenses, the Plan's termination and trust and fund liquidation, will revert to the
Company.
In the event that the Plan is terminated, the net assets of the Plan will be allocated for payment of Plan benefits to
the participants in an order of priority determined in accordance with ERISA, applicable regulations thereunder,
and the Plan document.
Certain benefits under the Plan are insured by the PBGC if the Plan terminates. Generally, the PBGC guarantees
most vested normal age retirement benefits, and certain disability and survivor’s pensions. However, the PBGC
does not guarantee all types of benefits under the Plan, and the amount of benefit protection is subject to certain
limitations. Vested benefits under the Plan are guaranteed at the level in effect on the date of the Plan’s
termination, subject to a statutory ceiling on the amount of an individual’s monthly benefit.
Whether all participants receive their benefits should the Plan be terminated at some future time will depend on
the sufficiency, at that time, of the Plan’s net assets to provide those benefits, the priority of those benefits to be
paid, and the level and type of benefits guaranteed by the PBGC at that time. Some benefits may be fully or
partially provided for by the then-existing assets and the PBGC guaranty, while other benefits may not be
provided at all.

9. Securities Lending
The Master Trust participates in a securities lending program through the Trustee. Under this program, the Master
Trust’s investment securities are loaned to investment brokers for a fee. Securities so loaned are fully
collateralized by cash and securities issued or guaranteed by the U.S. Government, its agencies and
instrumentalities. At December 31, 2024 and 2023, $15,009,745 and $19,293,509, respectively, of the Master
Trust’s securities were on loan under the Trustee’s securities lending program. The fair value of the collateral
received as a percentage of the total current value of the securities on loan by the Master Trust was
approximately 102% and 103% at December 31, 2024 and 2023, respectively. Income from the program of
$89,797 for the year ended December 31, 2024 is included in interest on the Master Trust’s statement of changes
in net assets available for benefits.
10. Derivative Financial Instruments
The Plan’s investment policy allows use of derivatives by selected investment managers for investment strategies
that include managing interest rate or credit risk, managing currency risk, reducing transaction costs by
substituting stock or bond futures, swaps or options for assets in the underlying cash market and enhancing
returns. Investment manager guidelines state that derivatives may not be used in a speculative manner or to
leverage the investment portfolio.
The Master Trust utilizes derivatives as economic hedges which are carried at fair value with changes recognized
in investment income.
Futures Contracts — The Master Trust may enter into futures contracts in the normal course of its investing
activities to manage market risk associated with the Master Trust’s equity and fixed income investments and to
achieve overall investment portfolio objectives. The Management of the Plan believes the credit risk associated
with these contracts is minimal, as they are traded on organized exchanges and settled daily.
Swap Contracts — The Master Trust may enter into swap contracts (e.g. interest rate, total return, credit default,
spread) to manage interest rate and/or curve risk, hedge spread sectors exposure and enhance return. Swaps are
counterparty agreements that can be standardized to the parties involved and trade over-the-counter. Although
the notional principal amount may be sizable, there is very little cash outlay (risk capital), as only the periodic
mark-to-market payments are generally netted in favor of the entitled party. Interest rate swaps trade in a highly
liquid market and management of the Master Trust believes the credit risk associated with these contracts is
minimal, as they are entered into with a number of highly-rated counterparties and have collateral backing the
position. The overall structure/concept of other types of swap contracts is similar, but the risk, return and form of
payment vary based on the specific swap contract and underlying exposures.
In addition, at December 31, 2024 and 2023 the Master Trust had credit default swaps outstanding. The Master
Trust will receive payment in the event of default of the corporate bonds covered by the swaps.
Currency Forwards — The Master Trust may enter into currency forward contracts in the normal course of its
investing activities to manage currency risk associated with the Master Trust’s equity and fixed income
investments. Currency forwards are counterparty agreements that can be standardized to the parties involved and
trade over-the-counter. Although the notional principal amount may be significant, there is very little cash outlay
(risk capital), as only the periodic mark-to-market payments are generally netted in favor of the entitled party.

11. Federal Income Tax Status
The Internal Revenue Service (the “IRS”) has determined and informed the Company by a letter dated June 24,
2014, that the Plan and related Master Trust were designed in accordance with applicable sections of the IRC.
The Plan has been amended since receiving the determination letter. However, the Company and Plan
management believe the Plan is currently designed and operated in compliance with applicable requirements of
the IRC, and the Plan and Master Trust continue to be tax-exempt. Therefore, no provision for income taxes has
been included in the Plan’s financial statements.
The Plan is subject to routine audits by taxing jurisdictions; however, there are currently no audits for any tax
periods in progress.
17

12. Exempt Party-In-Interest and Related Party Transactions
At both December 31, 2024 and 2023, the Master Trust held 1,000,000 shares of the Company’s common stock
with a cost basis of $25,670,000. For the year ended December 31, 2024, the Master Trust recorded dividend
income of $3,050,000 from the investment in the Company’s common stock. The Master Trust has a common
collective trust fund managed by the Trustee at December 31, 2024 and 2023 amounting to $58,781,483 and
$30,727,060, respectively. Interest income on such common collective trust fund amounted to $1,759,232 for the
year ended December 31, 2024.
Mercer, a wholly-owned subsidiary of the Company, determined the actuarial present value of the Plan’s
accumulated plan benefits.
Certain administrative functions are performed by officers and employees of the Company, who may also be
participants in the Plan, at no cost to the Plan.
These transactions are not deemed prohibited party-in-interest transactions because they are covered by
statutory or administrative exemptions from the IRC and ERISA’s rules on prohibited transactions.
13. Subsequent Events
Plan Management has performed its evaluation of subsequent events through October 1, 2025, the date the
financial statements were available to be issued, and has determined that there were no subsequent events
requiring adjustment to or disclosure in the financial statements.

ACTUARIAL METHODS
ASSET METHODS
The asset valuation method is an average of the adjusted market value for each year during the last 2
years preceding the valuation date. The adjusted market value is the market value at each
determination date adjusted to the valuation date based on actual cash flows and expected interest at
the lesser of the expected rate of return and the third segment rate. This amount is adjusted to be no
greater than 110% and no less than 90% of the fair market value, as defined in IRC Section 430.
A characteristic of this asset method is that, over time, it is slightly more likely to produce an actuarial
value of assets that is less than the market value of assets than an actuarial value that is greater than
the market value.
PARTICIPANT METHODS
The Plan is frozen so there are no additional benefit accruals. Participants or former participants are
included or excluded from the valuation as described below:
(cid:127) Participants included: Only those employees who have accrued benefits under the plan are
included in the valuation of liabilities.
(cid:127) Participants excluded: No actuarial liability is included for non-vested participants who terminated
prior to the valuation date. For this purpose, participants with a break in service on the valuation
date are treated as terminated participants.
(cid:127) Insurance contracts: The plan does not have any insurance contracts
MINIMUM FUNDING METHODS
The funding target for minimum funding calculations is computed using the traditional unit credit method
of funding. The objective under this method is to fund each participant’s benefits under the plan as they
accrue. Thus, the total pension to which each participant is expected to become entitled at retirement is
broken down into units, each associated with a year of past or future credited service.
A detailed description of the calculation follows:
(cid:127) The plan’s valuation date is the beginning of the plan year.
(cid:127) An individual’s funding target is the present value of future benefits based on the individual’s
frozen accrued benefit. If multiple decrements are used, the funding target for an individual is the
sum of the component funding targets associated with the various anticipated separation dates.
